      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fads in the Classroom</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Virginia M Donnelly letter on Sept 13 article scores New York City Education Board plan for number of 'staff development days' as waste of time and money</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report (Education page, Sept. 13) that the New York City Board of Education will close public high schools for five full days and other schools for six days this year for ''staff development.'' The board pulls the best teachers out of the classroom to become staff developers and deprives the students of instructional time in order to present unproven fads in teaching methods.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report (Education page, Sept. 13) that the New York City Board of Education will close public high schools for five full days and other schools for six days this year for ''staff development.'' The board pulls the best teachers out of the classroom to become staff developers and deprives the students of instructional time in order to present unproven fads in teaching methods.</p>
        <p>Smaller class sizes and having our students do more actual reading and math are the ways to improve their education. Why does the board persist in wasting time and money?</p>
        <p>VIRGINIA M. DONNELLY  New York, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
